questions.question:
The following program hangs or skips user input when reading a name after an age. Identify and fix the bug:

#include <iostream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    int age;
    std::cin >> age;
    std::string name;
    std::getline(std::cin, name);
    return 0;
}

questions.answer:
The 'std::cin >> age' statement leaves a newline character '\n' in the input stream buffer. When 'std::getline' runs, it sees that newline and thinks the user entered an empty line, so it skips the prompt. To fix this, use 'std::cin.ignore()' to clear the leftover newline before calling getline:

#include <iostream>
#include <string>
#include <limits>

int main() {
    int age{0};
    if (std::cin >> age) {
        std::cin.ignore(std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max(), '\n');
        std::string name;
        std::getline(std::cin, name);
    }
    return 0;
}

